description:
Saw little birds in the distance, zoomed in, stopped after two photos because I saw the white-throated sparrow and thought, well, I have plenty of much better photos of those… Just now going through camera roll realized it’s a white-throated sparrow scratching leaves on the ground, and a little warbler perched on a twig hoping for some stirred-up insects!

I was hoping at first that I’d caught a new/different warbler, but I think this is another yellow-rumped/myrtle warbler. I’m sure the experts will let me know if it’s not.

(Meanwhile I love how the little white-throated sparrows seem very happy to get along with other birds close by; I don’t see them squabbling and getting irritated, not just in mixed sparrow flocks but recently saw them turning over leaves under the bushes with a few young cardinals, and here one has a little warbler friend. Just cheerful round hungry little guys— and the white-striped versions are allegedly MORE aggressive than the tan-striped birds? Something else for me to keep an eye on… how many different foraging buddies can I find white-throated sparrows hanging out with (so far: house sparrows, dark-eyed juncos, white-crowned sparrows, cardinals, and a warbler…) and are there any predictable circumstances in this neighborhood that will make it easily observable for them to squabble and chase each other off a good resource, the way it’s easy to see in waterfowl or robins…?)

description: I’ve already posted similar terrible but barely-identifiable photos of barn swallows from under the Belmont bridge (and semi decent photos of conveniently stationary rough-winged swallows), and on this morning there were at least one pair of cliff swallows visible among them. The NRWS are easier to tell apart because they are plain brown/tan/white, but the cliff swallows and barn swallows are both very dark shiny blue on top and shades of rusty orange and white on the bottom. In person, I was able to notice their little white forehead marks shining in the sun first as they came in close under me, and then their light rumps as they turned away, and only occasionally in person could I tell their (relatively) short non-forked tails apart from the barn swallows, because they go too fast. I’m frankly amazed that I was able to snap this many photos that caught those features, though for each of these there are about a dozen vague shots over the side of the bridge with just a few pixels here and there.
I saw a tall brown bird standing still by the water. I took this picture at Montrose point bird sanctuary July 7, 2023. It was the morning and was 76 degrees for temperature

description:
NSFW if you are a swallow… while the barn swallows were just foraging around, these rough-winged swallows were courting and mating on this little patch of asphalt in the track-and-field area between Clark Park and Lane Tech. (There’s a shot-put circle with a safety net near there, but I’m not sure which sport this is for.) In-between landings, he was flying around while she watched - visible in some of the wide shots. Photo #2 is the only one where they didn’t both have their back to me, so I could see there was no brown band across the chest, so these are not bank swallows.

I was standing on the steps of the stadium to try and not block the sidewalk, and multiple people asked if I was taking pics of the geese, and then were very interested to watch the swallows swooping around once I pointed them out. :)

description:
Goose crèche! They’re finally old enough to hang out with their friends sometimes! (And a couple of mallards coming along for fun.)

None of the local families have 11 goslings, and you can also tell there are at least 3 different batches here - some with scruffy necks halfway turning from brown to black, some with sleeker almost-adult necks, and at least one I can see is still very yellow and smaller than the others. I believe my stand-offish “3’s” already posted before looked more mature than these guys last time we saw them and are probably not included, but the oldest of these could be my curious “4’s” who were a little younger-looking the last time I have photos - the babysitter adults are also more likely to be the parents of the 4 than the 3 (or some other habituated pair), because they crossed under the bridge to come see what I was looking at (and whether or not I had any food), and mom & dad of the 3 would’ve shepherded them AWAY from humans, not closer.

It’s a shame that there are “too many” geese, and that they poop on everything, because they are really smart and social and I really think they are so interesting and so pretty.
Found in Montrose Point Bird Sanctuary
Not what I expected to see when I turned around.

description: Was dropped by a hawk perching in schoolyard tree.

His swooping patrols back and forth over the water finally came closer to me when we were both near the boat dock, but I am not fast enough to catch him in flight (second to last pic he is a tiny little shape flying past), just perched from across the river. Haven’t seen the female since last month. 

Like the last few, I will say I’m marking this as adult male because females and juveniles have a second rusty belly stripe, and the top stripe on immature birds is a mix of blue and rust feathers. Clear white belly and clear blue top stripe = adult male.
